  1. Create a function called get_text with an argument for CSS values. The function should use the just-created movie_data list and return the text associated with the elements of interest. The functionâs steps should start with the movie-data object, pipe to a function to scrape the elements based on the input CSS argument, and extract the text from those elements as a character vector.
get_text <- function(css_values) {
  movie_data |>
    html_elements(css = css_values) |>
    html_text2()
}
  1. We will use get_text() as part of a strategy to scrape the elements of interest from movie_data.
  • The new DOM combines some formerly distinct elements into groups and eliminates their separate CSS selectors.
  • It is also true that not every element exists for a movie. Because the DOM uses generic classes for the list elements in some groups, it is not straightforward to figure out which scraped data goes with which movie. As an example, there are 25 movies but only 18 metascores.
  • However, we can scrape at the grouped class level and then figure out which data belongs where during cleaning.
  • We will scrape both the groups and the individual elements in cases where some elements in the group have their own class as it will simplify cleaning.

  1. Interpret the plot.

The chart shows that, over time, the number of votes for movies generally exhibits an upward trend, especially after the 1990s. This is indicated by the upward slope of the blue line (linear smoother). The violin plot provides the distribution of vote counts for different movie ratings, revealing that Not Rated films had a higher number of movies with votes below three hundred around the 1990s, while for R-rated films, most votes between 1995 and 2020 ranged from 0 to 300, with some movies also receiving votes between 300 and 800.

  1. Explain why the example plot legend has squares with no dots and what you could do to fix it.

R draws plots based on the order specified in our code. Since we first create the scatter plot, then overlay the violin plot, and finally add the regression line, the points for the âsquaresâ in the legend are obscured by the violin plot, resulting in the legend displaying âwith no dots.â We can resolve this issue by changing the code to draw the violin plot first and then the scatter plot.

ggplot(movies_df, aes(x = Year, y = Votes, color = Rating)) +
  geom_violin() +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "blue")

  1. Use the following code to establish an R Selenium session using a Firefox browser. Be sure you have followed the notes to have the latest versions of the browser and its drivers.
my_cssr <- c(
  ".dli-parent .ipc-title__text",
  ".dli-title-metadata",
  ".ipc-rating-star--rating",
  ".ipc-rating-star--voteCount",
  ".lfvcNT",

  ".cgTbSv"

library(RSelenium)

driver <- rsDriver(browser = "firefox", verbose = FALSE)
remote_driver <- driver$client
server <- driver$server


remote_driver$navigate("https://www.imdb.com/list/ls062615147/")

for (i in 1:5) {
  remote_driver$executeScript("window.scrollTo(0, document.body.scrollHeight);")
  Sys.sleep(0.1)  # wait for 0.1 seconds
}

movies100 <- map(my_cssr, function(css) {
  elements <- remote_driver$findElements(using = "css selector", value = css)
  texts <- map(elements, function(x) x$getElementText())  
})

remote_driver$close()
server$stop()
rm(driver, remote_driver, server, i)

How does the number of combined statistical areas (CSAs) relate to the number of Core-based areas across different states?

ggplot(wiki_df, aes(x = `CSAs`, y = `Core-based areas`)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  labs(title = "Relationship Between combined statistical areas (CSAs) and\nCore-based areas",
       x = "Number of combined statistical areas (CSAs)",
       y = "Number of Core-based areas") +
  geom_text(data = subset(wiki_df, Jurisdiction == "Texas"), 
            aes(label = Jurisdiction), 
            hjust = -0.2,
            color = "orange")
  1. Interpret the plot and answer your question.

From the graph, it can be seen that there is a strong positive linear relationship between combined statistical areas (CSAs) and core-based areas (CBAs). Additionally, it is worth noting that Texas has a particularly high ratio of CBAs to CSAs, which may indicate that the state faces challenges in overall economic development and regional planning. This situation necessitates greater attention to cross-regional cooperation and integration to promote economic growth and resource sharing.

It is easiest if the site is a static site for the data of interest and does not depend upon you clicking on the page to expose the data. However, those are getting rarer. If it is a site that is dynamic, but you can scrape the first page that loads, that is fine as long as you can produce a reasonable plot.
